Rhinocerebral mucormycosis (RCM) may result in severe intracranial ischemic and 
hemorrhagic lesions. Both computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance 
imaging (MRI) play an essential role in the diagnosis of RCM, but whereas CT is 
better for assessing bone erosion, MRI is superior in evaluating soft tissue, 
intraorbital extension, and in assessing intracranial and vascular invasion. 
Specific CT and MRI techniques, such as CT angiography or enhanced MR 
angiography, and more advanced MRI sequences such as gadolinium-3D Black Blood 
imaging, contribute to the assessment of the extension of vascular invasion.In 
